******
[2]
Date: Thu 30 Aug 2012
Source: Regnum News Agency [in Russian, machine trans., edited]
http://www.regnum.ru/news/1566382.html


According to the information provided by Rospotrebnadzor [Federal Service for Consumer Protection and Human Welfare] on 30 Aug 2012, 5 residents of Altai Territory have been hospitalized with clinical symptoms of anthrax.

Laboratory diagnosis was confirmed for 4; 8 more people, who had contact with sick and dead animals, are under the supervision of physicians. All are hospitalized in a satisfactory condition. New patients have been identified since 27 Aug 2012.

Those living in the administration of the Altai region are reminded of the restrictive measures imposed on the territories of the 3 settlements of Druzhba, Ruposovo (on 25 Aug 2012), and Marushka (on 27 Aug 2012). On the same dates the Altai Territory Veterinary Department approved plans for anti-epizootic measures to prevent the spread of the disease and eliminate it.

Veterinary specialists of the Altai region will deliver a package of measures to prevent the spread of the disease among animals. [Quarantine] barriers have been established on the borders of the villages. Vaccination of all susceptible animals was continued in these villages, and 4769 head of cattle were vaccinated. Illness and death of animals with suspected anthrax in the villages have not been observed. On 26 Aug 2012, stables where sick or dead animals were found were disinfected, as well as the places where the carcasses were butchered and the place of incineration.

Specialists from Altai Rospotrebnadzor in conjunction with specialists from the local Healthcare and Pharmaceutical Industry Department continue to implement preventive and anti-epidemic measures, including door-to-door visits, medical supervision of villagers, and foci disinfection activities in the villages of Druzhba and Marushka in Tselinny area. According to the results of medical surveillance, patients in the villages have been identified and the required medicines and disinfectants have been provided.

Immunization is continuing on the livestock farms. The population has been informed about preventive measures. All measures are being taken to contain the disease and prevent its further spread. Daily meetings are held by the anti-epidemic commission. The issue is under constant personal control of the Governor of the Altai Territory, Alexander Karlin.

--
